reasoning:
Well, forgive me if I jump right to the first principle – circle of competence. Google’s business is rooted in complex algorithms, digital advertising auctions and cloud computing platforms. That’s not a cake I know how to bake – my experience lies in simple, durable consumer brands, insurance float and railroads, not ad tech.

Speaking of moats, Google certainly has one. Its search engine and ad network are as entrenched as Coke’s secret syrup, driven by scale, network effects and data advantages. In that regard, it reminds me of a wide moat business like Coca-Cola.

On management, Alphabet’s team under Sundar Pichai is thoughtful and long-term oriented, allocating capital into AI and cloud while returning cash to shareholders. They strike me as honest operators, though I confess I haven’t studied their decisions as closely as I have at companies like See’s Candies or Geico.

Financially, they generate consistent profits and carry a strong balance sheet. But the digital ad market can be cyclical, and regulatory risk has crept onto my radar – a red flag I’d need to understand more thoroughly.

Valuation is impossible to pin down with the data at hand. We’ve got no revenue or earnings figures here, so assessing intrinsic value or margin of safety is out of reach.

Long term, Google’s scale and innovation could carry it forward two decades from now, but it’s a fast-changing field. I’d rather own an enduring franchise I truly grasp at a fair price.

Compared to opportunities in my own backyard – consumer staples, insurance and rails – this one sits outside my wheelhouse. In the absence of enough data or deep familiarity, I’m inclined to sit this dance out.

In short, this is a wonderful business by many measures, but it’s outside my circle. My default when in doubt is usually ‘no.’
